Horace here en» joins on the Roman dramatist the practice so strictly observed'among the Greeks, of confining the number of netors to three. In the origin of the drama the members of the chorus were the only performers. Thespis was his own actor, or, in other words, he first introduced an actor distinct from the chorus. sEschylus added a second, and Sophocles a third ; and this continued to be ever after the legitimate number. Hence, when three characters happened to be already on the stage, and a fourth was to come on, one of the three was obliged to retire‚ change his dress, and so return as the fourth personage.
